  "text": "The mouse APLP1 and APLP2 proteins share a large amount of sequence similarity with βPP in their N-terminal and C-terminal domains [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The region of these proteins corresponding to the Aβ domain of βPP, however, is less well conserved ( Fig. 2A) . The C-terminal domains of the βPP-like proteins mouse APLP1 and APLP2 directly aligning with the βC region of βPP were cloned, in frame, with the LexA protein in order to create Lex-APLP1 and Lex-APLP2 fusion protein expression constructs. Haploid L40 yeast strains containing the Fe65 pVP16-cDNA clone or pVP16-perlecan were mated with haploid JC1 strains containing Lex-βC, Lex-APLP1 and Lex-APLP2 fusion protein expression vectors. Diploid yeast were selected and the β-galactosidase filter assay was performed in order to assess transcriptional activation of the Lex A-driven β-galactosidase reporter gene due to interactions between Lex-ΑPP gene family C-terminal fusion proteins and the VP16-mouse Fe65 fusion protein, clone 230 (Fig. 2B ). During this filter assay, β-galactosidase activity was observed within 10-15 min with the Lex-APLP2 fusion protein. Lex-βC became visible within 20-30 min, and the Lex-APLP1 fusion protein construct developed more slowly, becoming appreciable 1 h after the addition of the β-galactosidase substrate. There was no activity observed for 2 days with any of the Lex A-fusion proteins when combined with the pVP16-perlecan construct whereas each of the Lex-ΑPP gene family fusion proteins became saturated with visible β-galactosidase activity within 2-3 h when combined with the VP16-Fe65 fusion protein.",
